Overview

The items selected for each condition should have a similar overall frequency. Here we check the frequency of the words for the two main predictors (i.e. conditions): analogical gender, phonological ending.

We have available frequencies from four corpora (in decreasing size):

  • ETC: 269.2 M words
  • EHME: 22.7 M words
  • ehitz: 3.5 M words
  • ahotsak: 2.7 M words

However, the last two (ehitz, ahotsak) are too small to provide reliable measures. Brysbaert et al. (2011) argue: “Word frequency measures should be based on a corpus of at least 20 million words.” All frequencies are log-normalised (base=10), and Laplace (additive) smoothing has been applied (Brysbaert et al. 2013).

Stimuli frequencies in context

The words in the stimuli are more frequent than 87% (according to EHME) or 85% (according to ETC) of the nouns in Basque (that is, they are within the top ~15% most frequent nouns). The plots below show the frequency of the stimuli items against the frequency distribution of all Basque nouns. The vertical line indicates the 3rd quartile in each corpus; all the stimuli are within the top quartile of the noun distribution in both corpora. In each plot, the upper set of words are those with a masc analogical gender, and the lower set are those with a fem analogical gender.

Frequencies by condition (Zipf)

We can further assess the mean frequencies for each experimental condition. The main predictors are es.gender (f, m) and eu.ending (a, o, i, n), which give a total of 8 conditions. Following van Heuven et al. (2014) we use the Zipf-scale as a thumb rule for high vs low frequencies. The Zipf-scale is similar to the log10 transformation but yields a 7-point scale. They consider Zipf-values higher than 4 ‘high-frequency’ words. All 8 conditions show a mean frequency above this threshold (>4) for both corpora (EHME, ETC).

eu.ending es.gender zipf_ehme zipf_etc
a f 4.43 4.15
a m 4.81 4.57
i f 4.84 4.56
i m 5.30 5.10
n f 4.38 4.19
n m 4.65 4.42
o f 4.70 4.72
o m 4.90 4.63

Even if the mean frequency for each condition is relatively high, there might be systematic differences across conditions.

Below, we explore (visually) and analyse (statistically) the frequency distribution for the different conditions. The position of the words in the plots is approximate (in order to avoid overlap).

Statistical tests

Follow-up on the tendencies shown by the plots using t-tests. Compare the frequencies in the two analogical-gender conditions: f vs m. In both corpora, words with es.gender=f are less frequent than es.gender=m. However, the difference is not statistically significant (p>.05).

corpus t.value estimate p.value
ehme_log -2.013275 -0.3293750 0.0532327
etc_log -1.950262 -0.2931659 0.0613736

Compare the frequencies for the two gender-prototypical endings: a vs o. Both EHME and ETC show a slightly lower frequency for the -a ending (prototypically fem) vs the -o ending (prototypically masc). Not statistically significant either.

corpus t.value estimate p.value
ehme_log -0.7074226 -0.1775000 0.4910534
etc_log -1.5027308 -0.3094939 0.1568151

A one-way analysis of the frequencies of the 8 conditions reveals that their means are not significantly different.

corpus F.value p.value
ehme_log 1.743798 0.2028228
etc_log 2.832729 0.0683167
